1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,166
♪♪♪

2
00:00:04,792 --> 00:00:06,124
[Saul]
Previously on "Homeland"...

3
00:00:06,125 --> 00:00:09,165
A panel of eight generals
and four admirals

4
00:00:09,166 --> 00:00:10,749
deemed that his actions
did not rise

5
00:00:10,750 --> 00:00:12,249
to the level
of a capital offense.

6
00:00:12,250 --> 00:00:14,040
You don't think that's a problem
for us going forward?

7
00:00:14,041 --> 00:00:17,416
- Is this him?
- What did she tell you?

8
00:00:17,417 --> 00:00:18,999
Nothing. I did not
tell him anything.

9
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:20,624
She told me you're ready
to testify.

10
00:00:20,625 --> 00:00:21,874
Nobody's testifying.

11
00:00:21,875 --> 00:00:25,457
This is Brett O'Keefe. Welcome
to Day 52 of the Resistance.

12
00:00:25,458 --> 00:00:28,165
[man] Easy. Easy, Mr. O'Keefe.
You're not under arrest.

13
00:00:28,166 --> 00:00:30,999
Now you said
put the country first.

14
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:32,708
I'm offering you an opportunity
to do just that.

15
00:00:32,709 --> 00:00:34,749
A job, you mean?

16
00:00:34,750 --> 00:00:37,082
How does National Security
Advisor sound?

17
00:00:37,083 --> 00:00:41,833
You have $38,000
in credit card debt

18
00:00:41,834 --> 00:00:44,582
and a variety of aliases.
You don't have a job.

19
00:00:44,583 --> 00:00:46,708
Please, tell me you realize
we've been here before.

20
00:00:46,709 --> 00:00:50,582
Jesus. You know, not every shred
of nonconventional behavior

21
00:00:50,583 --> 00:00:53,082
boils down to an onset
of hypomania.

22
00:00:53,083 --> 00:00:54,374
[car door closes]

23
00:00:54,375 --> 00:00:56,999
Sorry, sir. The President
asked for bug sweeps,

24
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:58,541
home and office,
all senior staff.

25
00:00:58,542 --> 00:01:00,916
Get the fuck out of my house.
Is that order clear?

26
00:01:00,917 --> 00:01:05,166
♪ tense music playing ♪

27
00:01:08,208 --> 00:01:09,208
[taps keys]

28
00:01:09,209 --> 00:01:14,125
♪♪♪

29
00:01:16,834 --> 00:01:20,541
[chains rattling]

30
00:01:20,542 --> 00:01:23,624
♪♪♪

31
00:01:23,625 --> 00:01:25,749
[thud]
Aah!

32
00:01:25,750 --> 00:01:27,082
[exhales sharply]

33
00:01:27,083 --> 00:01:28,999
♪♪♪

34
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,875
[exhales deeply]

35
00:01:39,542 --> 00:01:40,500
♪♪♪

36
00:01:40,501 --> 00:01:42,916
[Keane] He saved our lives.

37
00:01:42,917 --> 00:01:44,582
[Carrie] Yeah.

38
00:01:44,583 --> 00:01:48,082
What was his name?

39
00:01:48,083 --> 00:01:52,624
[Brody]
Carrie, you're not yourself.

40
00:01:52,625 --> 00:01:54,416
[Carrie] You don't have
my condition.

41
00:01:54,417 --> 00:01:56,749
I'm dealing with it.
I-I've been dealing with it

42
00:01:56,750 --> 00:01:59,374
since I was 22.

43
00:01:59,375 --> 00:02:00,916
♪♪♪

44
00:02:00,917 --> 00:02:04,541
[Maggie] She said no one at work
could know. She's bipolar.

45
00:02:04,542 --> 00:02:07,040
[man] The mood of the country,
it's not great.

46
00:02:07,041 --> 00:02:08,290
[siren wailing]

47
00:02:08,291 --> 00:02:11,082
[O'Keefe] Civil... War.

48
00:02:11,083 --> 00:02:13,290
[Carrie]
Madam President, please!

49
00:02:13,291 --> 00:02:16,207
You have to put a stop to this!

50
00:02:16,208 --> 00:02:18,541
[woman] It's only getting worse.

51
00:02:18,542 --> 00:02:20,541
[Quinn]
Is there no fucking line?

52
00:02:20,542 --> 00:02:24,708
[Hillary Clinton]
Ridiculous lies and accusations.

53
00:02:24,709 --> 00:02:27,666
♪♪♪

54
00:02:27,667 --> 00:02:31,249
[woman] The White House
is in crisis mode.

55
00:02:31,250 --> 00:02:34,958
[Saul] We're talking
about information warfare.

56
00:02:34,959 --> 00:02:37,749
[Carrie] Our country
is under attack.

57
00:02:37,750 --> 00:02:39,249
♪♪♪

58
00:02:39,250 --> 00:02:41,791
[O'Keefe]
The time to rise up is now!

59
00:02:41,792 --> 00:02:44,290
♪♪♪

60
00:02:44,291 --> 00:02:47,708
[Carrie] I swore an oath
to protect it.

61
00:02:47,709 --> 00:02:50,082
[siren wailing]

62
00:02:50,083 --> 00:02:53,040
[Quinn] Just think of me
as a light on the heavens,

63
00:02:53,041 --> 00:02:57,333
a beacon steering you clear
of the wrongs.

64
00:03:00,667 --> 00:03:05,499
[O'Keefe] An American hero died
last night.

65
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:07,791
Jamie McClendon,

66
00:03:07,792 --> 00:03:10,290
three star general.

67
00:03:10,291 --> 00:03:14,833
An early casualty
in our revolution.

68
00:03:14,834 --> 00:03:19,916
He will not be the last.

69
00:03:19,917 --> 00:03:23,541
They say he died
of a heart attack,

70
00:03:23,542 --> 00:03:27,749
that he just keeled over
and died.

71
00:03:27,750 --> 00:03:30,958
Nothing could be done, okay?

72
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:35,708
A heart attack.

73
00:03:35,709 --> 00:03:37,708
This marine's marine

74
00:03:37,709 --> 00:03:41,249
who went through six tours
of Afghanistan and Iraq

75
00:03:41,250 --> 00:03:44,249
without so much as a head cold.

76
00:03:44,250 --> 00:03:46,374
A heart attack.

77
00:03:46,375 --> 00:03:48,624
This force of nature

78
00:03:48,625 --> 00:03:51,874
who could outrun recruits
half his age...

79
00:03:51,875 --> 00:03:54,750
he just dropped dead?

80
00:03:56,625 --> 00:03:59,290
That's what they want us
to believe.

81
00:03:59,291 --> 00:04:02,624
♪ ominous music playing ♪

82
00:04:02,625 --> 00:04:06,624
Even though the prison guard
responsible for his safety

83
00:04:06,625 --> 00:04:09,499
grew up on the very same block

84
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:12,999
as the President's
Chief of Staff.

85
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:15,165
That's right,

86
00:04:15,166 --> 00:04:18,457
David Wellington
and that prison guard...

87
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:21,249
they grew up together.

88
00:04:21,250 --> 00:04:24,082
But the General...
Oh, his heart just kinda...

89
00:04:24,083 --> 00:04:26,749
[makes splatting sound]

90
00:04:26,750 --> 00:04:28,165
...gave out.

91
00:04:28,166 --> 00:04:31,999
You expect us to believe that?

92
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:33,332
Really?!

93
00:04:33,333 --> 00:04:37,374
The President called
for his death.

94
00:04:37,375 --> 00:04:41,749
The tribunal said no, but this
Hitler in the White House...

95
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:45,624
Oh! She will not be denied!

96
00:04:45,625 --> 00:04:49,916
The only way to stop
this violence against us,

97
00:04:49,917 --> 00:04:52,874
this violence of lies,

98
00:04:52,875 --> 00:04:55,582
is to fight back

99
00:04:55,583 --> 00:04:58,749
with a clenched fist of truth!

100
00:04:58,750 --> 00:05:02,082
♪♪♪

101
00:05:02,083 --> 00:05:04,874
[Keane] How did it happen?

102
00:05:04,875 --> 00:05:07,958
[Attorney General] It appears
he had a heart attack.

103
00:05:07,959 --> 00:05:10,458
So it's just bad luck.

104
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:13,457
Brett O'Keefe says
one of the prison guards

105
00:05:13,458 --> 00:05:15,791
was a childhood friend
of Mr. Wellington's.

106
00:05:15,792 --> 00:05:18,916
Is that true?

107
00:05:18,917 --> 00:05:20,582
Not that we could establish.

108
00:05:20,583 --> 00:05:22,791
It's bullshit, obviously.

109
00:05:22,792 --> 00:05:25,457
That may be, but at least
O'Keefe has an explanation

110
00:05:25,458 --> 00:05:29,290
for what happened, which, as far
as I can tell, we do not,

111
00:05:29,291 --> 00:05:31,124
because even I don't believe

112
00:05:31,125 --> 00:05:33,833
that a decorated soldier
in perfect health

113
00:05:33,834 --> 00:05:36,165
suddenly drops dead
of a coronary

114
00:05:36,166 --> 00:05:40,499
the moment he sets foot
in federal custody.

115
00:05:40,500 --> 00:05:43,040
Why don't you get back to us,

116
00:05:43,041 --> 00:05:46,499
if and when you actually
know something?

117
00:05:46,500 --> 00:05:47,916
[sips]

118
00:05:47,917 --> 00:05:49,834
Madam President.

119
00:05:54,959 --> 00:05:55,999
[door opens]

120
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,332
[door closes]

121
00:05:58,333 --> 00:06:00,040
You shouldn't listen
to O'Keefe.

122
00:06:00,041 --> 00:06:02,165
My listening to O'Keefe
is not the problem.

123
00:06:02,166 --> 00:06:04,749
Well, it is if you think
that I used someone

124
00:06:04,750 --> 00:06:07,332
I supposedly knew in third grade
to off McClendon.

125
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:09,999
I don't think that.
They do, out there,

126
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:13,583
because that is what
O'Keefe is telling them.

127
00:06:14,834 --> 00:06:17,708
You know what we need to do?
Change the con...

128
00:06:17,709 --> 00:06:20,833
Change the conversation.
Yeah, you keep saying.

129
00:06:20,834 --> 00:06:23,582
Well,
I have an idea for that.

130
00:06:23,583 --> 00:06:27,416
It involves Saul Berenson...
and 200 others.

131
00:06:27,417 --> 00:06:28,833
A mass release.

132
00:06:28,834 --> 00:06:30,874
So they can keep
plotting against me.

133
00:06:30,875 --> 00:06:32,791
Most of them were
nowhere near the conspiracy.

134
00:06:32,792 --> 00:06:35,374
Most of them haven't been
adequately questioned yet.

135
00:06:35,375 --> 00:06:38,749
After two months,
that's on us.

136
00:06:38,750 --> 00:06:41,165
Releasing them would be
a show of good faith.

137
00:06:41,166 --> 00:06:42,541
How about someone shows me
some good faith?

138
00:06:42,542 --> 00:06:44,749
Not gonna happen.
That's the point.

139
00:06:44,750 --> 00:06:47,582
As long as everyone who's anyone
in this town has a friend

140
00:06:47,583 --> 00:06:50,708
or a colleague or a goddamn
family member behind bars,

141
00:06:50,709 --> 00:06:53,958
you will get no cooperation
anywhere, no traction.

142
00:06:53,959 --> 00:06:58,582
Things will only get worse.
Either you release them...

143
00:06:58,583 --> 00:07:00,290
Or what?

144
00:07:00,291 --> 00:07:03,082
Or what, David?

145
00:07:03,083 --> 00:07:04,416
Either you release them

146
00:07:04,417 --> 00:07:07,290
or get ready to incarcerate
the whole town,

147
00:07:07,291 --> 00:07:08,916
because it's not just
Brett O'Keefe

148
00:07:08,917 --> 00:07:11,542
gunning for you anymore.
It's everyone.

149
00:07:16,542 --> 00:07:17,958
[switch clicks]

150
00:07:17,959 --> 00:07:20,749
That's weird.

151
00:07:20,750 --> 00:07:22,749
Right when I was
calling her Hitler

152
00:07:22,750 --> 00:07:25,416
for, like, the tenth time,
I could feel myself

153
00:07:25,417 --> 00:07:29,959
leave my body and float up next
to that jar of peaches there.

154
00:07:31,417 --> 00:07:34,040
Brett.

155
00:07:34,041 --> 00:07:35,041
Well, hello.

156
00:07:37,458 --> 00:07:39,582
[footsteps ascend stairs]

157
00:07:39,583 --> 00:07:43,709
♪♪♪

158
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:51,124
[cheers and applause]

159
00:07:51,125 --> 00:07:52,332
Thank you!

160
00:07:52,333 --> 00:07:54,457
[applause continues]

161
00:07:54,458 --> 00:07:56,082
Thank you!

162
00:07:56,083 --> 00:07:59,040
[applause continues]

163
00:07:59,041 --> 00:08:00,541
Clenched fist of truth.

164
00:08:00,542 --> 00:08:01,500
[chuckles] I like that.

165
00:08:01,501 --> 00:08:04,749
So do I. That's why I stole it.

166
00:08:04,750 --> 00:08:07,290
[laughter]

167
00:08:07,291 --> 00:08:09,040
My word.

168
00:08:09,041 --> 00:08:10,124
America.

169
00:08:10,125 --> 00:08:13,290
Yes, sir. And this...

170
00:08:13,291 --> 00:08:16,290
First battle of the Civil War,
fought right over there.

171
00:08:16,291 --> 00:08:18,791
Five miles
past the tree line.

172
00:08:18,792 --> 00:08:20,999
- Philippi.
- Philippi.

173
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:23,999
Now I was taught it was
Fort Sumpter, out at the coast.

174
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,165
This was
the first land battle.

175
00:08:26,166 --> 00:08:29,207
June 3, 1861.

176
00:08:29,208 --> 00:08:30,582
Governor of Virginia didn't
know what side he was on.

177
00:08:30,583 --> 00:08:33,958
It was a state of confusion
in the people.

178
00:08:33,959 --> 00:08:37,833
I'd say there's a lot less
confusion this time around,

179
00:08:37,834 --> 00:08:40,666
thanks to you.

180
00:08:40,667 --> 00:08:44,000
No, I-I mean it.
Show him, J.J.

181
00:08:45,625 --> 00:08:47,291
Come on. Show him.

182
00:08:54,125 --> 00:08:55,332
Rebel!

183
00:08:55,333 --> 00:08:56,792
"Re-bel."

184
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:03,833
Holy shit, it's me!

185
00:09:03,834 --> 00:09:08,417
[laughter]

186
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:14,708
I'm not utterly clueless.
I-I know.

187
00:09:14,709 --> 00:09:18,332
Getting my niece involved
in my... business

188
00:09:18,333 --> 00:09:23,207
was a huge lapse
of judgment.

189
00:09:23,208 --> 00:09:25,874
[sighs deeply]
But I-I... [sighs]

190
00:09:25,875 --> 00:09:28,708
was running out of options,
and... and... and... and...

191
00:09:28,709 --> 00:09:32,541
Honestly, the whole situation
was so unique,

192
00:09:32,542 --> 00:09:34,582
I can basically guarantee
that won't happen again.

193
00:09:34,583 --> 00:09:39,708
And what is it?
This... this business.

194
00:09:39,709 --> 00:09:42,207
Uh, it was meeting, uh,
that needed to be relocated

195
00:09:42,208 --> 00:09:43,083
at the last second.

196
00:09:43,084 --> 00:09:45,291
And what about
the credit card debt?

197
00:09:46,750 --> 00:09:48,749
[scoffs] Was there
a segue there I missed?

198
00:09:48,750 --> 00:09:52,124
I'm just trying to understand
the whole picture.

199
00:09:52,125 --> 00:09:53,833
You have a home,
with your sister.

200
00:09:53,834 --> 00:09:56,582
You have a place to live.
And yet, at the same time,

201
00:09:56,583 --> 00:09:59,582
you're checked into
at least two expensive hotels

202
00:09:59,583 --> 00:10:01,624
for I'm not sure
what purpose.

203
00:10:01,625 --> 00:10:04,416
You want to explain that?

204
00:10:04,417 --> 00:10:06,708
Well, obviously,
you're talking to my sister.

205
00:10:06,709 --> 00:10:10,749
- Why not ask her?
- I have talked to her, yes.

206
00:10:10,750 --> 00:10:13,958
- She's concerned about you.
- About credit cards?

207
00:10:13,959 --> 00:10:17,582
No, not just.
She said you lost someone,

208
00:10:17,583 --> 00:10:18,458
that a friend of yours...

209
00:10:18,459 --> 00:10:22,374
maybe your best friend...

210
00:10:22,375 --> 00:10:25,417
died violently
in front of your eyes.

211
00:10:29,667 --> 00:10:30,917
Yeah. [sniffles]

212
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:37,375
You know what? He would have
understood what I'm doing.

213
00:10:38,041 --> 00:10:39,791
He never let me down, ever.

214
00:10:39,792 --> 00:10:42,666
He would be right here
with me now.

215
00:10:42,667 --> 00:10:44,165
[sighs]

216
00:10:44,166 --> 00:10:46,874
[voice breaks]
He would have gotten it.

217
00:10:46,875 --> 00:10:48,666
Gotten what exactly?

218
00:10:48,667 --> 00:10:49,917
[sighs]

219
00:10:53,041 --> 00:10:56,874
Our country is under attack,

220
00:10:56,875 --> 00:10:59,708
and I am called on...
to protect it.

221
00:10:59,709 --> 00:11:02,124
Not like it's something
I feel I should do,

222
00:11:02,125 --> 00:11:05,541
if I can find the time.
I mean, I swore an oath,

223
00:11:05,542 --> 00:11:07,666
just like my friend did,

224
00:11:07,667 --> 00:11:11,165
to do something,
to the best of my ability

225
00:11:11,166 --> 00:11:13,999
to help my country,
which I am doing.

226
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,833
And what my sister fails
to comprehend...

227
00:11:15,834 --> 00:11:19,207
[scoffs]
is that I'm making progress.

228
00:11:19,208 --> 00:11:22,249
Okay.

229
00:11:22,250 --> 00:11:24,249
Okay.

230
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:26,791
Let me ask you.

231
00:11:26,792 --> 00:11:29,333
How does that sound to you,
what you just said?

232
00:11:31,667 --> 00:11:33,417
It sounds true.

233
00:11:35,041 --> 00:11:36,290
And?

234
00:11:36,291 --> 00:11:41,666
And I'm taking my medication,
if that's what you're asking.

235
00:11:41,667 --> 00:11:43,207
- I take it every day.
- Lithium?

236
00:11:43,208 --> 00:11:47,249
That's been your principal
therapy for 15 years now, right?

237
00:11:47,250 --> 00:11:50,458
- Prescribed by your sister.
- Originally.

238
00:11:51,667 --> 00:11:54,040
Are you aware that

239
00:11:54,041 --> 00:11:56,457
in a small part
of the population,

240
00:11:56,458 --> 00:11:59,417
Lithium can become ineffective
after that much time?

241
00:12:00,917 --> 00:12:03,792
It simply stops working.

242
00:12:13,583 --> 00:12:15,583
[buzzer, clank]

243
00:12:18,834 --> 00:12:20,040
[door locks]

244
00:12:20,041 --> 00:12:24,207
Good news. The President
has accepted your terms.

245
00:12:24,208 --> 00:12:27,040
She's agreed to release you,
along with the 200 others,

246
00:12:27,041 --> 00:12:28,332
just like you asked,

247
00:12:28,333 --> 00:12:31,749
provided you accept a position
in her administration...

248
00:12:31,750 --> 00:12:34,249
National Security Advisor.

249
00:12:34,250 --> 00:12:35,450
Can I ask why
the sudden shift?

250
00:12:37,750 --> 00:12:39,666
President had
a change of heart.

251
00:12:39,667 --> 00:12:41,250
[buzzer in distance]

252
00:12:42,792 --> 00:12:45,208
Was this before or after
General McClendon died?

253
00:12:46,417 --> 00:12:49,000
- Does it matter?
- Yeah, David, it matters.

254
00:12:51,750 --> 00:12:53,541
Because if my new position
is really shit screen

255
00:12:53,542 --> 00:12:56,749
for the administration,
I'm not interested.

256
00:12:56,750 --> 00:12:59,207
You'd rather have 200 people
sitting in jail?

257
00:12:59,208 --> 00:13:00,542
Yeah.

258
00:13:02,250 --> 00:13:06,916
First, I don't think that you
or anyone actually believes

259
00:13:06,917 --> 00:13:08,791
that the President
of the United States

260
00:13:08,792 --> 00:13:11,082
had a General offed
in prison.

261
00:13:11,083 --> 00:13:15,749
Second, no one's expecting you
to pick up pom-poms

262
00:13:15,750 --> 00:13:17,457
and become some kind of
cheerleader.

263
00:13:17,458 --> 00:13:18,958
Good.

264
00:13:18,959 --> 00:13:22,165
But no carping
from the sidelines either.

265
00:13:22,166 --> 00:13:25,500
No press leaks undermining
the President's statements.

266
00:13:29,208 --> 00:13:31,040
We want...

267
00:13:31,041 --> 00:13:32,083
a partner.

268
00:13:33,583 --> 00:13:34,624
We want to leave
the mess behind

269
00:13:34,625 --> 00:13:38,333
and move
the country forward.

270
00:13:39,625 --> 00:13:42,624
When does this happen?

271
00:13:42,625 --> 00:13:45,291
This, uh, moving.

272
00:13:47,375 --> 00:13:49,041
Soon as you say yes.

273
00:13:51,709 --> 00:13:56,583
♪ dramatic music playing ♪

274
00:14:09,083 --> 00:14:12,082
[sighs]

275
00:14:12,083 --> 00:14:13,291
[exhales deeply]

276
00:14:14,375 --> 00:14:19,332
[breathing deeply]

277
00:14:19,333 --> 00:14:24,207
[continues breathing deeply]

278
00:14:24,208 --> 00:14:29,083
♪♪♪

279
00:14:36,375 --> 00:14:37,834
[taps key]

280
00:14:45,542 --> 00:14:48,583
[taps keyboard]

281
00:14:49,667 --> 00:14:50,667
[sighs]

282
00:14:55,917 --> 00:14:58,041
[door opens on screen]

283
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:13,625
♪♪♪

284
00:15:18,583 --> 00:15:19,999
Madam President.

285
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:23,999
- [Keane] You know your lines?
- Think so.

286
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,207
"Time to move on."

287
00:15:26,208 --> 00:15:27,582
That's what my advisors say.

288
00:15:27,583 --> 00:15:29,041
Thank you.

289
00:15:34,125 --> 00:15:36,166
But realistically?

290
00:15:38,417 --> 00:15:40,040
The national security
establishment came after me

291
00:15:40,041 --> 00:15:43,124
with machine guns
as far as I can see

292
00:15:43,125 --> 00:15:46,208
for no other reason than that
they felt disrespected.

293
00:15:50,291 --> 00:15:54,000
I doubt I'll ever get over it.
I'm not even sure I should.

294
00:15:55,083 --> 00:15:57,332
It was a very small group,
Madam President.

295
00:15:57,333 --> 00:16:00,290
- You're sure about that.
- Yes.

296
00:16:00,291 --> 00:16:03,082
And it never included me.

297
00:16:03,083 --> 00:16:07,791
I was there that day with you,
in the lead vehicle.

298
00:16:07,792 --> 00:16:10,290
My driver was killed
in the explosion.

299
00:16:10,291 --> 00:16:11,916
The doctors
spent three hours

300
00:16:11,917 --> 00:16:14,417
pulling broken glass
out of my face.

301
00:16:16,375 --> 00:16:17,834
I was on your side.

302
00:16:19,709 --> 00:16:21,457
I hope so.

303
00:16:21,458 --> 00:16:23,290
[door opens]

304
00:16:23,291 --> 00:16:24,331
[Wellington]
They're ready.

305
00:16:33,834 --> 00:16:38,667
♪ tense music playing ♪

306
00:16:54,208 --> 00:16:57,666
[typing]

307
00:16:57,667 --> 00:16:59,833
[computer whooshes]

308
00:16:59,834 --> 00:17:04,917
♪♪♪

309
00:17:09,542 --> 00:17:11,000
[buttons clicking]

310
00:17:14,500 --> 00:17:16,500
[cellphone rings]

311
00:17:18,583 --> 00:17:19,833
[ring]

312
00:17:19,834 --> 00:17:22,916
[indistinct conversations]

313
00:17:22,917 --> 00:17:25,124
[ring]

314
00:17:25,125 --> 00:17:29,708
[beep]
Sorry. Gotta deal with this.

315
00:17:29,709 --> 00:17:32,541
- [Carrie] Hello?
- What is this?

316
00:17:32,542 --> 00:17:34,165
I'm not sure. She's... she's got
some connection to Wellington.

317
00:17:34,166 --> 00:17:36,332
A colleague, maybe?
A secret girlfriend?

318
00:17:36,333 --> 00:17:39,624
I meant, what the fuck
are you doing, calling me?

319
00:17:39,625 --> 00:17:41,916
Look, I don't need you to do
anything except I.D. her.

320
00:17:41,917 --> 00:17:43,416
Do that, and... and I'll
take care of the rest.

321
00:17:43,417 --> 00:17:45,082
I-I know you're under
a microscope there.

322
00:17:45,083 --> 00:17:46,582
Look, what about
our last encounter

323
00:17:46,583 --> 00:17:48,457
suggested I ever wanted to hear
from you again?

324
00:17:48,458 --> 00:17:50,874
I just need you to I.D. her.
It's important.

325
00:17:50,875 --> 00:17:54,165
- I'm on my own here.
- And why do you think that is?

326
00:17:54,166 --> 00:17:56,541
[sighs] Look... I...

327
00:17:56,542 --> 00:17:58,165
[cellphone beeps]

328
00:17:58,166 --> 00:18:00,582
Hello?

329
00:18:00,583 --> 00:18:03,792
Dante? Are you there?
[knock on door]

330
00:18:10,375 --> 00:18:13,290
- Who were you talking to?
- Nobody. [sighs]

331
00:18:13,291 --> 00:18:14,833
Sorry.
I-I-I wasn't snooping.

332
00:18:14,834 --> 00:18:15,874
I came up
because there's something

333
00:18:15,875 --> 00:18:18,208
I think you'll want to see.

334
00:18:21,250 --> 00:18:23,249
[amplified voice]
What began as an investigation

335
00:18:23,250 --> 00:18:24,083
into a violent conspiracy

336
00:18:24,084 --> 00:18:26,999
against the heart
of our government

337
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:28,582
has become a source

338
00:18:28,583 --> 00:18:32,249
of such acrimony and division

339
00:18:32,250 --> 00:18:36,082
that I've decided,
in the interest of this country,

340
00:18:36,083 --> 00:18:39,416
it is time to put it behind us.

341
00:18:39,417 --> 00:18:43,916
A group that has come
to be known as "The Two Hundred"

342
00:18:43,917 --> 00:18:45,833
is being released today
as we speak.

343
00:18:45,834 --> 00:18:49,499
[applause and murmuring]

344
00:18:49,500 --> 00:18:51,374
Among those released today,

345
00:18:51,375 --> 00:18:53,040
is Saul Berenson,

346
00:18:53,041 --> 00:18:55,708
my new
National Security Advisor.

347
00:18:55,709 --> 00:19:01,541
[applause on TV]

348
00:19:01,542 --> 00:19:03,666
[Saul]
Thank you, Madam President...

349
00:19:03,667 --> 00:19:05,708
Mommy, Uncle Saul's on TV!

350
00:19:05,709 --> 00:19:08,207
...for this... great honor.

351
00:19:08,208 --> 00:19:09,999
We cannot let recent events

352
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:14,290
derail the work of this nation.

353
00:19:14,291 --> 00:19:14,917
We are still one nation.

354
00:19:14,918 --> 00:19:17,749
What is this?

355
00:19:17,750 --> 00:19:20,791
Her new
National Security Advisor.

356
00:19:20,792 --> 00:19:22,207
Saul?

357
00:19:22,208 --> 00:19:24,791
[Maggie] It's what you wanted,
isn't it? He's out.

358
00:19:24,792 --> 00:19:27,999
[Saul] ...and while we squabble,
they gain ground.

359
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:30,165
While we attack our own
government, they revel

360
00:19:30,166 --> 00:19:32,499
- in their good luck.
- I don't get it.

361
00:19:32,500 --> 00:19:34,457
[Bill] What's to get?

362
00:19:34,458 --> 00:19:36,624
Um, why he's joining them.

363
00:19:36,625 --> 00:19:37,708
Well, for one thing,

364
00:19:37,709 --> 00:19:40,374
because those 200 people
you've been obsessing about,

365
00:19:40,375 --> 00:19:42,457
the political prisoners,
so-called?

366
00:19:42,458 --> 00:19:45,916
- They're being released.
- What?

367
00:19:45,917 --> 00:19:49,165
Released. All of them.
So... you were wrong.

368
00:19:49,166 --> 00:19:50,874
The President
is not a dictator.

369
00:19:50,875 --> 00:19:52,040
The world is not coming
to an end.

370
00:19:52,041 --> 00:19:54,499
[Maggie] Shh. I wanna hear this.
By the end of the day,

371
00:19:54,500 --> 00:19:56,416
they will all be released...
an event that you swore

372
00:19:56,417 --> 00:19:57,833
wouldn't occur
during in our lifetimes.

373
00:19:57,834 --> 00:19:59,124
Let's see
if it actually happens.

374
00:19:59,125 --> 00:20:00,499
Most of them are already out.

375
00:20:00,500 --> 00:20:03,541
[scoffs] They never should've
been in, in the first place.

376
00:20:03,542 --> 00:20:06,499
[Bill] You never admit
you're wrong, do you?

377
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:07,749
♪♪♪

378
00:20:07,750 --> 00:20:10,457
[Saul, amplified voice]
...what the mass release shows

379
00:20:10,458 --> 00:20:12,833
is that the system works.

380
00:20:12,834 --> 00:20:13,583
[people asking questions
at once]

381
00:20:13,584 --> 00:20:15,499
Yes?

382
00:20:15,500 --> 00:20:17,040
What about
your own incarceration?

383
00:20:17,041 --> 00:20:18,958
Are you saying now
that it was justified?

384
00:20:18,959 --> 00:20:21,708
What's important is not that
I was in, but that I'm out,

385
00:20:21,709 --> 00:20:23,416
standing in front of you.
It's testimony

386
00:20:23,417 --> 00:20:27,666
to the open-mindedness
of this administration...

387
00:20:27,667 --> 00:20:29,165
[lowered voice]
Have you told him?

388
00:20:29,166 --> 00:20:32,332
[lowered voice] Not yet. Wanted
to see how he did on this first.

389
00:20:32,333 --> 00:20:33,749
[Saul] ...to addressing
the many security challenges

390
00:20:33,750 --> 00:20:35,958
this country is facing
around the world.

391
00:20:35,959 --> 00:20:36,959
- [all shouting at once]
- Yes, sir?

392
00:20:36,960 --> 00:20:38,917
What will be your first order
of business?

393
00:20:39,667 --> 00:20:42,207
Finding my office. Thank you.

394
00:20:42,208 --> 00:20:45,416
[scattered laughter, applause]

395
00:20:45,417 --> 00:20:48,374
Well,
they didn't lynch me.

396
00:20:48,375 --> 00:20:51,541
You did well. Thank you.

397
00:20:51,542 --> 00:20:54,249
So? What next?

398
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:57,082
David will get you started.

399
00:20:57,083 --> 00:20:58,416
What's that mean?

400
00:20:58,417 --> 00:21:01,124
It's what the reporter
was asking,

401
00:21:01,125 --> 00:21:02,791
your first order of business.

402
00:21:02,792 --> 00:21:04,541
[Saul] I have some thoughts
on that.

403
00:21:04,542 --> 00:21:06,249
Well, so does the President.

404
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:09,958
She feels it's important
to send the right message,

405
00:21:09,959 --> 00:21:11,791
- to the country.
- What sort of message?

406
00:21:11,792 --> 00:21:15,457
Well, we have a very troubling
national security situation

407
00:21:15,458 --> 00:21:17,916
that's grown more and more
out of control.

408
00:21:17,917 --> 00:21:20,290
What has?

409
00:21:20,291 --> 00:21:21,417
O'Keefe.

410
00:21:25,375 --> 00:21:27,916
Okay, wait.

411
00:21:27,917 --> 00:21:30,582
- We just announced an amnesty.
- Not for him.

412
00:21:30,583 --> 00:21:33,082
He was working directly
with Dar Adal.

413
00:21:33,083 --> 00:21:35,624
So was I. You just made me
National Security Advisor.

414
00:21:35,625 --> 00:21:37,999
Saul, he's been thumbing
his nose at an arrest warrant

415
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,082
for six weeks, calling for
the overthrow of the government.

416
00:21:41,083 --> 00:21:43,374
The President's questioning
the FBI's commitment

417
00:21:43,375 --> 00:21:47,332
to bring him in at all.
It has to stop.

418
00:21:47,333 --> 00:21:51,082
Since when is domestic police
work in my job description?

419
00:21:51,083 --> 00:21:52,958
We see this
as hunting a terrorist.

420
00:21:52,959 --> 00:21:56,124
President trusts you.

421
00:21:56,125 --> 00:21:57,875
She wants you in charge.

422
00:22:02,125 --> 00:22:04,708
Good night, beautiful girl.

423
00:22:04,709 --> 00:22:06,375
Mmm. [kisses] Sleep tight.

424
00:22:08,542 --> 00:22:11,749
- You okay?
- I like it here.

425
00:22:11,750 --> 00:22:13,124
So do I.

426
00:22:13,125 --> 00:22:15,374
Then why are you mad
all the time?

427
00:22:15,375 --> 00:22:16,208
Hmm?

428
00:22:16,209 --> 00:22:19,083
Like yelling at Uncle Bill.

429
00:22:21,709 --> 00:22:25,082
Oh, I wasn't yelling, sweetie.
We just... disagreed.

430
00:22:25,083 --> 00:22:28,333
You always disagree.

431
00:22:30,750 --> 00:22:32,874
I'll try to be nicer.
Okay?

432
00:22:32,875 --> 00:22:34,708
I don't want to have
to leave here.

433
00:22:34,709 --> 00:22:36,792
I don't know where we'd go.

434
00:22:38,166 --> 00:22:39,125
Oh, sweetheart, is that what
you're worried about,

435
00:22:39,126 --> 00:22:40,500
where we'd go?

436
00:22:43,458 --> 00:22:45,666
Listen to me.

437
00:22:45,667 --> 00:22:48,666
This is our family,
yours and mine.

438
00:22:48,667 --> 00:22:52,290
We don't have to go anywhere.
All right?

439
00:22:52,291 --> 00:22:54,833
♪ somber music playing ♪

440
00:22:54,834 --> 00:22:57,040
[whispers] I love you,
Franny Banany.

441
00:22:57,041 --> 00:22:59,499
Mmm. [kisses]

442
00:22:59,500 --> 00:23:02,166
Now get some sleep.
Night.

443
00:23:04,500 --> 00:23:05,958
[switch clicks]

444
00:23:05,959 --> 00:23:11,083
♪♪♪

445
00:23:28,709 --> 00:23:30,625
[door squeaks closed]

446
00:23:34,667 --> 00:23:36,333
[sighs heavily]

447
00:23:37,417 --> 00:23:38,750
[exhales deeply]

448
00:23:41,083 --> 00:23:42,916
[switch clicks]

449
00:23:42,917 --> 00:23:48,834
♪♪♪

450
00:23:59,542 --> 00:24:00,625
[taps key]

451
00:24:34,375 --> 00:24:37,457
♪♪♪

452
00:24:37,458 --> 00:24:38,583
[taps key]

453
00:24:52,208 --> 00:24:57,333
♪♪♪

454
00:24:59,208 --> 00:25:01,624
[laptop chimes faintly]

455
00:25:01,625 --> 00:25:05,332
[birds chirping]

456
00:25:05,333 --> 00:25:07,917
[sighs]
[laptop chimes]

457
00:25:09,625 --> 00:25:10,834
[laptop chimes]

458
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:24,207
[typing]

459
00:25:24,208 --> 00:25:26,375
[laptop chimes]

460
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:30,500
[laptop chimes]

461
00:25:32,333 --> 00:25:35,874
[typing]

462
00:25:35,875 --> 00:25:38,000
[laptop chimes]

463
00:25:40,542 --> 00:25:41,792
[laptop chimes]

464
00:25:47,333 --> 00:25:49,666
[taps key, laptop whirring]

465
00:25:49,667 --> 00:25:50,958
[Franny] Mommy!

466
00:25:50,959 --> 00:25:52,457
- Oh!
- Help.

467
00:25:52,458 --> 00:25:56,374
Oh, sweetie,
you missed a button.

468
00:25:56,375 --> 00:25:57,375
Here.

469
00:25:57,376 --> 00:25:59,374
[laptop whooshes]

470
00:25:59,375 --> 00:26:00,541
What's wrong?

471
00:26:00,542 --> 00:26:04,207
Uh, nothing. Why don't you, uh,
go start your breakfast?

472
00:26:04,208 --> 00:26:06,374
I'll be down in
a second, okay? Okay.

473
00:26:06,375 --> 00:26:09,875
♪ suspenseful music playing ♪

474
00:26:14,041 --> 00:26:16,708
[taps key]

475
00:26:16,709 --> 00:26:18,040
♪♪♪

476
00:26:18,041 --> 00:26:19,291
[exhales deeply]

477
00:26:20,792 --> 00:26:22,250
[exhales deeply]

478
00:26:26,625 --> 00:26:27,625
[Maggie] Carrie?

479
00:26:27,626 --> 00:26:31,082
Carrie, can you please
come down?

480
00:26:31,083 --> 00:26:36,250
♪♪♪

481
00:26:44,834 --> 00:26:46,416
Hey. What's going on?

482
00:26:46,417 --> 00:26:48,332
My meeting got moved
an hour earlier,

483
00:26:48,333 --> 00:26:50,666
so can you take the girls
to school?

484
00:26:50,667 --> 00:26:54,207
- [Josie] I can do it.
- [Maggie] No. So, Carrie?

485
00:26:54,208 --> 00:26:57,791
Um... [sighs] I wish I could,
but I-I have an interview.

486
00:26:57,792 --> 00:27:00,374
- [Maggie] Drop them on the way.
- [Josie] I can do it.

487
00:27:00,375 --> 00:27:02,416
[keys jangle]
No.

488
00:27:02,417 --> 00:27:04,666
[Carrie] It's on Skype,
in about ten minutes.

489
00:27:04,667 --> 00:27:06,416
Looking like that?

490
00:27:06,417 --> 00:27:08,833
Um, I-I'm about to change.
I'm sorry.

491
00:27:08,834 --> 00:27:11,791
So I either reschedule
my meeting again,

492
00:27:11,792 --> 00:27:14,290
or I take her right now.
She ready?

493
00:27:14,291 --> 00:27:15,208
Uh, yeah. Yeah, she's ready.

494
00:27:15,209 --> 00:27:17,583
[Maggie] Okay, Franny.
Let's go, sweetie.

495
00:27:19,417 --> 00:27:21,499
Have a good day at school.
All right, munchkin?

496
00:27:21,500 --> 00:27:23,959
- Mwah. [kisses] Love you.
- Good luck.

497
00:27:25,959 --> 00:27:26,625
The interview.

498
00:27:26,626 --> 00:27:29,624
Yeah, thanks. And thanks.

499
00:27:29,625 --> 00:27:31,624
[Maggie] Yeah.
Come on, girls, let's go.

500
00:27:31,625 --> 00:27:32,958
[door closes]

501
00:27:32,959 --> 00:27:37,834
♪♪♪

502
00:27:49,208 --> 00:27:51,499
Fuck!

503
00:27:51,500 --> 00:27:53,290
[sighs]

504
00:27:53,291 --> 00:27:58,417
[gunshots]

505
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:01,666
[laughing]

506
00:28:01,667 --> 00:28:05,165
No better feeling,
is there?

507
00:28:05,166 --> 00:28:08,791
Exercising
your constitutional rights.

508
00:28:08,792 --> 00:28:11,290
- You wanna try?
- I'm good.

509
00:28:11,291 --> 00:28:12,457
You're gonna want to.

510
00:28:12,458 --> 00:28:15,834
Uncle Dan...
he's got a surprise.

511
00:28:18,750 --> 00:28:22,457
[laughing]

512
00:28:22,458 --> 00:28:24,999
- That is hilarious!
- I told you you'd want to.

513
00:28:25,000 --> 00:28:26,499
[laughs]

514
00:28:26,500 --> 00:28:29,667
Well, why the hell not?

515
00:28:33,041 --> 00:28:35,124
You know what people forget?

516
00:28:35,125 --> 00:28:39,541
The Second Amendment isn't
about needing guns for hunting

517
00:28:39,542 --> 00:28:42,040
or... or target shootin'
